# Tool quirks

> **DELETE OR REPLACE THIS FILE.** This is an example Tier 2 memory leaf showing the shape of a tool-quirks reference. Replace its contents with quirks you actually encounter, then rename the file to `tool_quirks.md` (drop the `.example`).

A scratchpad for system-level idiosyncrasies — the things that aren't bugs in your code, they're just *how this tool behaves on this machine*. Keep entries one-paragraph, with the symptom first, then the workaround.

## Format

```
### <tool or domain> — <one-line symptom>

**Symptom:** What goes wrong.
**Cause:** Why (if known).
**Workaround:** What to do instead. Pin a version, set an env var, swap out the tool, etc.
```

## Examples to inspire your real entries

(Replace with actual quirks you hit. These are illustrative only.)

### Bash on macOS — bash 3.2 default

**Symptom:** Modern bash features (associative arrays, `declare -n` namerefs, `${var,,}` lowercasing) fail with "bad substitution" or syntax errors.
**Cause:** macOS ships with bash 3.2 by default; modern features need 4+.
**Workaround:** Use `/opt/homebrew/bin/bash` (Homebrew bash) for scripts that need newer features, or stick to portable POSIX shell idioms.

